3. flatMap()
      Concept :
          flatMap() is an intermediate operation used to flatten nested structures (such as a list of lists) into a single stream. It first converts each element into a stream and then combines all those streams into one.
          
          Syntax:
          
          stream.flatMap(element -> element.stream())




1. Given a list of lists of integers, flatten it into a single list of integers.
--> Program
        import java.util.Arrays;
        import java.util.List;
        
        public class FlatMapNumbers {
            public static void main(String[] args) {
        
                List<List<Integer>> numbers = Arrays.asList(
                        Arrays.asList(1, 2, 3),
                        Arrays.asList(4, 5),
                        Arrays.asList(6, 7, 8)
                );
        
                numbers.stream()
                        .flatMap(List::stream)
                        .forEach(System.out::println);
            }
        }
        Output
        1
        2
        3
        4
        5
        6
        7
        8




2. Given a list of sentences, return a list of all unique words.
-->Program
    import java.util.Arrays;
    import java.util.List;
    public class UniqueWords {
        public static void main(String[] args) {
    
            List<String> sentences = Arrays.asList(
                    "Java is powerful",
                    "Java is easy",
                    "Streams are powerful"
            );
    
            sentences.stream()
                    .flatMap(sentence -> Arrays.stream(sentence.split(" ")))
                    .distinct()
                    .forEach(System.out::println);
        }
    }
    Output
    Java
    is
    powerful
    easy
    Streams
    are
    
    Note: split(" ") converts each sentence into an array of words, flatMap() combines them into one stream, and distinct() removes duplicates.







3. Convert a list of departments, where each department has a list of employees, into a list of all employees.
Program
import java.util.Arrays;
import java.util.List;

class Employee {
    String name;

    Employee(String name) {
        this.name = name;
    }
}

class Department {
    String name;
    List<Employee> employees;

    Department(String name, List<Employee> employees) {
        this.name = name;
        this.employees = employees;
    }
}

public class DepartmentExample {
    public static void main(String[] args) {

        Department d1 = new Department(
                "IT",
                Arrays.asList(
                        new Employee("Ravi"),
                        new Employee("Anil")
                )
        );

        Department d2 = new Department(
                "HR",
                Arrays.asList(
                        new Employee("Priya"),
                        new Employee("Kiran")
                )
        );

        List<Department> departments = Arrays.asList(d1, d2);

        departments.stream()
                .flatMap(dept -> dept.employees.stream())
                .map(emp -> emp.name)
                .forEach(System.out::println);
    }
}
Output
Ravi
Anil
Priya
Kiran



| Question                 | Stream Methods Used        | Transformation                                         |
| ------------------------ | -------------------------- | ------------------------------------------------------ |
| Flatten list of integers | `flatMap(List::stream)`    | `List<List<Integer>> → Stream<Integer>`                |
| Find unique words        | `flatMap()` + `distinct()` | `List<String> → Stream<String>`                        |
| Get all employees        | `flatMap()` + `map()`      | `List<Department> → Stream<Employee> → Stream<String>` |





Interview Tip
map() vs flatMap()

Suppose you have:

List<List<Integer>> list = Arrays.asList(
    Arrays.asList(1, 2),
    Arrays.asList(3, 4)
);
Using map()
list.stream()
    .map(List::stream)
    .forEach(System.out::println);

Output

java.util.stream.ReferencePipeline$Head@...
java.util.stream.ReferencePipeline$Head@...

Here, each list is converted into a separate Stream, resulting in a Stream<Stream<Integer>>.

Using flatMap()
list.stream()
    .flatMap(List::stream)
    .forEach(System.out::println);

Output

1
2
3
4

Here, flatMap() combines all inner streams into a single Stream<Integer>.

Quick Difference
----------------
| `map()`                                      | `flatMap()`                             |
| -------------------------------------------- | --------------------------------------- |
| One-to-one transformation                    | One-to-many transformation + flattening |
| Produces `Stream<Stream<T>>` for nested data | Produces `Stream<T>`                    |
| Used for simple transformations              | Used for nested collections             |
